def preprocess_text(text):
    if isinstance(text, str):

        text = text.lower()

        text = re.sub(r'http\S+', '', text)


        text = re.sub(r'[^a-z#@]', ' ', text)

        text = re.sub(r'@[A-Za-z0-9]+', '', text)

        text = re.sub(r'#', '', text)

        text = re.sub(r'\s+', ' ', text).strip()

        text = re.sub(r'\b[\w\-.]+?@\w+?\.\w{2,4}\b', '', text)

        text = re.sub(r'@\w+', '', text)

        text = re.sub(r'\b\w{1,2}\b', '', text)

    return text

def remove_stopwords(tokens):
    if isinstance(tokens, list):
        return [word for word in tokens if word not in stopwords.words('english')]
    else:
        return []

def lemmatization(tokens):
    if isinstance(tokens, list):
        lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
        return ' '.join(lemmatizer.lemmatize(token) for token in tokens)
    else:
        return ''

# DefinING function to convert text to word2vec vectors
def text_to_vectors(text, word_vectors):
    vectors = []
    for word in text:
        if word in word_vectors:
            vectors.append(word_vectors[word])
    return np.array(vectors)

# Defining  the TransformerBlock layer
class TransformerBlock(Layer):
    def __init__(self, embedding_dim, num_heads, dff, rate=0.1):
        super(TransformerBlock, self).__init__()

        self.attention = MultiHeadAttention(num_heads=num_heads, key_dim=embedding_dim // num_heads)
        self.ffn = Sequential([
            Dense(dff, activation='relu'),
            Dense(embedding_dim)
        ])

        self.layernorm1 = LayerNormalization(epsilon=1e-6)
        self.layernorm2 = LayerNormalization(epsilon=1e-6)

        self.dropout1 = Dropout(rate)
        self.dropout2 = Dropout(rate)

    def call(self, inputs, training=False):
        attn_output = self.attention(inputs, inputs)
        attn_output = self.dropout1(attn_output, training=training)
        out1 = self.layernorm1(inputs + attn_output)

        ffn_output = self.ffn(out1)
        ffn_output = self.dropout2(ffn_output, training=training)
        out2 = self.layernorm2(out1 + ffn_output)

        return out2

In [ ]:
# Create the transformer model
def create_transformer_model(max_sequence_length, num_classes, embedding_dim):
    inputs = Input(shape=(max_sequence_length,))
    embedding_layer = Embedding(num_words, embedding_dim, weights=[embedding_matrix], input_length=max_sequence_length, trainable=False)(inputs)
    transformer_block = TransformerBlock(embedding_dim, num_heads=2, dff=64, rate=0.1)(embedding_layer)
    average_pooling = GlobalAveragePooling1D()(transformer_block)
    outputs = Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')(average_pooling)
    model = Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)
    return model

from sklearn.model_selection import KFold

# Defining the number of folds for cross-validation
num_folds = 3

split_index = len(X_pad) // 4


X_set = X_pad[:split_index]
y_set = y_categorical[:split_index]

# Initialize KFold
kf = KFold(n_splits=num_folds, shuffle=True, random_state=42)

accuracy_scores = []

# Performing cross-validation
fold_index = 1
for train_index, test_index in kf.split(X_set):
    print(f"Fold {fold_index}/{num_folds}:")
    X_train_fold, X_val_fold = X_set[train_index], X_set[test_index]
    y_train_fold, y_val_fold = y_set[train_index], y_set[test_index]


    model = create_transformer_model(max_sequence_length, num_classes, embedding_dim)
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])


    model.fit(X_train_fold, y_train_fold, batch_size=64, epochs=3, validation_data=(X_val_fold, y_val_fold))

    _, accuracy = model.evaluate(X_val_fold, y_val_fold)
    print("Validation Accuracy:", accuracy)
    accuracy_scores.append(accuracy)

    fold_index += 1

# Calculate and print average accuracy across folds
avg_accuracy = np.mean(accuracy_scores)
print("Average Accuracy:", avg_accuracy)

In [ ]:
def create_transformer_model(max_sequence_length, num_classes, embedding_dim, num_heads, dff, rate):
    inputs = Input(shape=(max_sequence_length,))
    embedding_layer = Embedding(num_words, embedding_dim, weights=[embedding_matrix], input_length=max_sequence_length, trainable=False)(inputs)
    transformer_block = TransformerBlock(embedding_dim, num_heads, dff, rate)(embedding_layer)
    average_pooling = GlobalAveragePooling1D()(transformer_block)
    outputs = Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')(average_pooling)
    model = Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)
    return model

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# Split the data into training and testing sets, taking 25% of the total data for training
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_pad, y_categorical, test_size=0.25, random_state=42)

# Define hyperparameters to tune for the first iteration
hyperparameters_iteration1 = {
    'num_heads': [2, 4],
    'dff': [64, 128],
    'rate': [0.1, 0.2]
}

# Define hyperparameters to tune for the second iteration (with rational changes)
hyperparameters_iteration2 = {
    'num_heads': [4, 8],
    'dff': [128, 256],
    'rate': [0.2, 0.3]
}

# Performing hyperparameter tuning
for iteration, hyperparameters in enumerate([hyperparameters_iteration1, hyperparameters_iteration2], start=1):
    print(f"Iteration {iteration}:")
    for num_heads in hyperparameters['num_heads']:
        for dff in hyperparameters['dff']:
            for rate in hyperparameters['rate']:
                print(f"Hyperparameters: num_heads={num_heads}, dff={dff}, rate={rate}")

                # Create and compile the model with current hyperparameters
                model = create_transformer_model(max_sequence_length, num_classes, embedding_dim, num_heads, dff, rate)
                model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

                # Train the model
                model.fit(X_train, y_train, batch_size=64, epochs=3, validation_split=0.2)

                # Evaluate the model on the testing set
                _, accuracy = model.evaluate(X_test, y_test)
                print("Testing Accuracy:", accuracy)

                # Print accuracy and hyperparameters for each iteration
                print("Accuracy:", accuracy)
                print("Hyperparameters:", f"num_heads={num_heads}, dff={dff}, rate={rate}")
                print()

Rational changes

  • Number of Heads (num_heads):

first iteration : I consider [2, 4] as the possible values for the number of heads.

second iteration : I increased the range to [4, 8]. This change allows me to explore larger values for the number of heads, potentially capturing more complex patterns in the data.

  • Dimension of Feedforward Network:

  • first iteration : I considered [64, 128] as the possible values for the dimension of the feedforward network.

  • second iteration : I increased the range to [128, 256]. By doing so, I aimed to explore larger dimensions for the feedforward network, which might capture more intricate relationships in the data.

  • Dropout Rate
  • first iteration :I consider [0.1, 0.2] as the possible values for the dropout rate.
  • second iteration : I increased the range to [0.2, 0.3]. This change introduces higher dropout rates, which can help prevent overfitting by regularizing the model more effectively.
